These were the most important fights of the year 1644 ; 
and die Kmg was yet (as both himself and others thought) 
in as good condition as the Parliament, which despaired of 
victory, by the commanders they then used Therefore they 
voted a new modelling of the army, suspecting the Earl of 
Essex, though I think wrongfully, to be too much a royalist, 
for not having done so much as they looked for, in this 
second batUe at Newbury. The Earls of Essex and Man- 
chester, perceiving what they went about, voluntarily laid 
down their commissions ; and the House of Commons made 
